The first time I submitted a proposal, I refreshed my inbox for three days straight. The reply was a rejection. I stared at the screen, unsure whether to feel embarrassed or determined. I chose determined — and that choice changed everything.

A few years ago, if someone had asked me to write an NGO funding proposal for WinVinaya Foundation, I would not have known where to begin. Today, proposal writing is one of my strongest professional skills — and it has directly contributed to securing CSR and philanthropic funding that has changed lives in Bengaluru and beyond. Looking back, the journey has been filled with learning, mentorship, rejections, and ultimately, success. But none of it was a straight line.

My First Proposal: A Lesson in Humility
I still remember sitting down to create my very first proposal. I did not know how to structure it. I did not know how to write it. I did not even know what questions to ask.
Fortunately, I had two people who believed I could figure it out. Baskaran Sir patiently guided me through the entire process — teaching me how different sections fit together, how to present ideas clearly, and how to think about what a donor actually needs to read. Shiva Sir brought a different lens, always pushing us to make the proposal sharper and more compelling.
Together, we finished my first proposal. We submitted it with hope. We did not win.
That first rejection stung. So did the second. And the third. But something interesting happened with each one — I stopped seeing them as failures and started seeing them as feedback. Every rejected proposal taught me something I could not have learned any other way.

"Rejection is not the end of the story. It is the first draft."

How AI Became My Learning Partner (ChatGPT, Claude & Gemini for Nonprofits)
One of the biggest turning points in my growth was learning how to use AI tools effectively. And I want to be honest about why: my English writing skills were not strong enough to create professional proposals on my own in the beginning.
ChatGPT helped me find my voice. It helped me organise scattered thoughts into coherent arguments and turn rough ideas into polished language. Perplexity and Google Gemini helped me research donor priorities and understand the landscape before writing a single sentence.
More recently, Claude changed how I work with formatting. What used to take me nearly an hour — structuring and polishing a proposal — now takes me 5 to 10 minutes. That time saved goes back into thinking more carefully about strategy and impact.
But here is what I want to be clear about: AI never did my thinking for me. It helped me think better. The ideas, the understanding of the problem, the connection between the project and the donor's goals — that still had to come from me.

AI Tools I Use for Proposal Writing
Tool	Primary Use	Time Saved	Best For
ChatGPT	Organising ideas, voice development	30–45 min per draft	First drafts, language clarity
Perplexity	Donor research, sector landscape	1–2 hrs research	Pre-writing research
Google Gemini	Understanding donor priorities	45–60 min	Contextual research
Claude	Formatting, structuring, polishing	50–55 min per proposal	Final structure & presentation

Why NGO Proposal Writing Is Never a Straight Line
Most people imagine proposal writing as a simple process: write the document, submit it, wait for a response. My experience has been completely different.
There have been many times when we believed a proposal was finished — only for someone in the final review to suggest a new angle that made it significantly stronger. We would then go back, revise large sections, and rebuild parts of the proposal from scratch. It could be exhausting.
Even after submission, donors and clients often come back with questions or suggestions. We would revisit the proposal again, refine it further, and realign it with their expectations.
Yes, working on the same proposal five or six times can be tiring. But every revision sharpened my thinking. Every question made me understand the problem more deeply. Every conversation with a donor taught me something about how decisions are actually made.

"A proposal is not simply a document. It is a bridge between a problem and a solution — and bridges take time to build properly."

What Actually Makes a CSR Proposal Win
After facing enough rejections and winning enough proposals, I began to notice a pattern. Successful proposals are not won by better writing. They are won by better thinking — and that thinking has to happen before a single word is written.
The first step is never writing. The first step is questioning.

5 Questions I Ask Before Writing Every Proposal
1.  Who is this donor, and what do they truly care about? Align to their stated priorities, not just your organisation's needs.
2.  What specific problem are we solving? Not in theory — in practice, in their geography, in their sector.
3.  How does our work connect to their goals? The link should feel inevitable, not forced.
4.  What impact can we prove? Past data, testimonials, and measurable outcomes matter more than intentions.
5.  Does our budget tell an honest story? A well-constructed budget demonstrates that you understand the real cost of change — and that you will be responsible with every rupee.

I also learned — largely from Baskaran Sir — that a budget tells a story just as much as the narrative does. A well-constructed budget does not just list numbers. It demonstrates that you understand the real cost of change, and that you will be responsible stewards of every rupee.
Shiva Sir taught me something equally important: always think from the donor's perspective. Before you write anything, sit in their chair. Ask what they are worried about. Ask what success looks like for them. When you understand that, your proposal stops being a request and starts being a partnership.

From Rejections to Real Impact: WinVinaya Foundation's Funding Wins
The most meaningful part of this journey has been watching years of hard work translate into real outcomes.
For WinVinaya Foundation, we successfully secured a CSR project and a three-year philanthropic project. These were not lucky breaks. They were the result of dozens of rejected proposals, hundreds of revisions, and the kind of patience that only comes from genuinely believing in the work you are doing.
Behind every successful proposal is a real outcome — individuals with disabilities and women from underserved communities who got trained, placed, and employed in dignified jobs. In FY 2025–26 alone, 54 individuals were placed across 9 sectors through our programs. That is what the proposals are for.
I remember the moment we heard about our first successful proposal. It was not just a professional milestone — it was proof that the process worked. That persistence, feedback, and mentorship could turn a nervous beginner into someone capable of creating real change.

A New Chapter: Working Independently
This year marked an important milestone for me personally. I began creating proposals independently — without relying on Baskaran Sir's direct support throughout the process. I still seek guidance and feedback, and I always will. But being able to take a proposal from idea to submission on my own gave me a kind of confidence I had not felt before.
It was a quiet but significant moment. A reminder that growth is sometimes invisible until one day you look back and realise how far you have come.
Yet I remain a student. Every new proposal brings a challenge I have not encountered before. Every donor conversation shifts my understanding. Every project teaches me something I could not have learned any other way.

To Anyone Just Starting Out in NGO Proposal Writing
If you are learning something new and feeling overwhelmed, I want to tell you something I wish someone had told me earlier:

💡 Key Lessons from My Proposal Writing Journey
✦  Your first attempt will not be perfect. Do it anyway.
✦  Rejection is feedback in disguise — collect it, learn from it, use it.
✦  Seek mentors who challenge you, not just ones who comfort you.
✦  Use every tool available to you — including AI — but never let them replace your thinking.
✦  The donor's perspective matters more than your own. Always sit in their chair first.
✦  A budget is a story. Write it with care.
✦  Stay curious. The moment you think you know everything is the moment you stop growing.

"I am still learning — and that is the most exciting part."


